**Synchronous vs Asynchronous Programming in JavaScript**
===========================================================

In JavaScript, programming styles can be categorized into two main types: synchronous and asynchronous.

**Synchronous Programming**
-------------------------

Synchronous programming is a style where the code executes one line at a time, in a linear fashion. Each statement must complete before the next one starts. This means that if a function takes a long time to execute, it will block the entire program until it finishes.

### Example: Synchronous Code

```javascript
console.log("Start");
function exampleFunction() {
  console.log("Inside exampleFunction()");
  // Simulate a time-consuming operation
  for (let i = 0; i < 1000000000; i++) {}
  console.log("End of exampleFunction()");
}
exampleFunction();
console.log("End");
```

In this example, the `for` loop inside `exampleFunction()` will take some time to complete. The program will be blocked until it finishes.

**Asynchronous Programming**
---------------------------

Asynchronous programming is a style where multiple tasks can run concurrently. When an asynchronous operation starts, it does not block the entire program. Instead, it returns control back to the main thread, allowing other operations to continue executing.

### Example: Asynchronous Code using Callbacks

```javascript
console.log("Start");
function exampleFunction(callback) {
  console.log("Inside exampleFunction()");
  // Simulate a time-consuming operation
  setTimeout(() => {
    console.log("End of exampleFunction()");
    callback();
  }, 2000);
}
exampleFunction(() => {
  console.log("Callback executed");
});
console.log("End");
```

In this example, the `setTimeout()` function is used to simulate an asynchronous operation that takes 2 seconds to complete. The program will continue executing and print "End" before the callback is executed.

**Example: Asynchronous Code using Promises**

```javascript
console.log("Start");
function exampleFunction() {
  console.log("Inside exampleFunction()");
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    // Simulate a time-consuming operation
    setTimeout(() => {
      console.log("End of exampleFunction()");
      resolve();
    }, 2000);
  });
}
exampleFunction().then(() => {
  console.log("Promise resolved");
});
console.log("End");
```

In this example, the `exampleFunction()` returns a Promise that resolves after 2 seconds. The program will continue executing and print "End" before the promise is resolved.

**Example: Asynchronous Code using async/await**

```javascript
console.log("Start");
async function exampleFunction() {
  console.log("Inside exampleFunction()");
  await new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    // Simulate a time-consuming operation
    setTimeout(() => {
      console.log("End of exampleFunction()");
      resolve();
    }, 2000);
  });
}
exampleFunction().then(() => {
  console.log("async/await finished");
});
console.log("End");
```

In this example, the `exampleFunction()` is marked as async and uses await to wait for the promise to resolve. The program will continue executing and print "End" before the async function finishes.

Note that while these examples illustrate the differences between synchronous and asynchronous programming, they do not necessarily represent best practices or real-world scenarios.
